\section{High-Level Planner}

This section covers the high-level planner, which operates on the topological map and decides to which room the robot should drive and which high-level task, like explore or search, the robot should execute in this room. The goal of the planner is to minimize the expected search time, which is a reasonable for object search. Other possibilities would be maximizing the probability of finding the object in limited time or minimizing the time until a certain confidence about the existence of a searched object is reached. These tackle slightly different problems, but the results should be quiet similar in most scenarios. The high-level planner is called when a search task is started and also every time a low-level tasks finishes.


\subsection{High-Level Planning}

The objective of the high-level planner is to find the optimal search path visiting all not already searched rooms $\mathbf{p^*}=(r_1,r_2,...,r_{\mathbf{|R|}})$ with $r_i$ being the $i^{th}$ room to search and $\mathbf{|R|}$ being the number of found rooms given a starting room $r_0$. A valid search path contains every not already searched room exactly once. In this work the optimal path is the valid path with the minimal expected search time.
\begin{equation}
 \mathbf{p^*}=\argminA_{\mathbf{p} \in valid paths} E(t|\mathbf{p},r_0) 
\end{equation}

The expected search time given a staring room $r_0$ and a search path $\mathbf{p}$ can be calculated with
\begin{equation}
 E(t|\mathbf{p},r_0) = \sum_{i=1}^{\mathbf{|p|}} (\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}(1-P_{r_j}(O))(M_{r_{i-1},r_i}+P_{r_i}(O)E_{r_i}+(1-P_{r_i})T_{r_i})
\end{equation}
This means for every room the time to move to the room plus the expected time to search the room multiplied by the probability of not stopping the search earlier is added. Searching rooms with high object probabilities first results in a lower expected search time as the probability that another room has to be searched is reduced. 

The valid paths can be seen as the leaf nodes in a tree, where the root is an empty path and the other nodes are incomplete paths. The optimal path is the leave node with the minimal expected search time. The tree representation helps to find an efficient implementation as the recursive structure in the calculation of the expected search time is obvious and pruning techniques can be applied. 

\subsection{Generation of next High-Level task}

The search path contains only the order, in which the rooms are searched. To execute the search path tasks have to be generated, which are then planned and executed by the low-level planner. These high-level tasks are 
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{move through doorway:} The robot should drive through the doorway connecting the current room and the target room.
 \item \textbf{turn around:} The robot should execute a 360° rotation to gather information
 \item \textbf{explore room:} The robot should explore the current room to obtain a complete 2D map of the room and find all doorways in the room
 \item \textbf{search room:} The robot should search for the target object in the current room
\end{itemize}

Figure \ref{fig: HLTask} shows how the next high-level task, which should be executed, is generated. To do this the high-level planner keeps track of which rooms were already visited, which rooms are explored and which rooms were already searched.

